  "prompt": "Does Google take into account that you are speeding while calculating your ETA?",
  "response": "Google Maps does not directly track or use your actual speed to calculate your Estimated Time of Arrival (ETA) in real time. However, it does use a combination of historical traffic data, real-time traffic conditions, and other factors like road type, speed limits, and typical travel patterns to estimate how long it will take you to reach your destination.\n\nHere\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Historical Traffic Data**: Google uses aggregated data from past trips on that route to predict travel times.\n2. **Real-Time Traffic Conditions**: If there\u2019s congestion, accidents, or other delays, Google adjusts the ETA based on current conditions.\n3. **Speed Limits**: Google often incorporates speed limits into its calculations, especially on highways and major roads.\n4. **User Data**: While Google doesn\u2019t track your speed directly, it may use anonymized data from other users to refine its predictions.\n\nThat said, if you are speeding, your actual arrival time might be earlier than the ETA, but Google does not account for your individual driving behavior in its calculations for legal and privacy reasons. Always follow posted speed limits and drive safely!",
